      "content": "The legal standard for a \"correct\" interpretation is not a single, objective truth; rather, it is determined by the prevailing legal methodology. Originalism, which seeks the Founders' intent, is the most rigorous standard for grounding constitutional law. Judicial restraint, which demands judges stick strictly to the text, is the other core legal principle used to judge legitimacy. Therefore, the debate isn't about a factual error, but about which foundational legal philosophy—originalism or living constitutionalism—you believe should govern the Court.",
      "source": "target",
